{"title_page": "Mr. Peanut", "text_new": "{{short description|Mascot for Planters Peanuts}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mr. Peanut\n| full_name          = Bartholomew Richard Fitzgerald-Smythe<ref name=FullName>{{cite web |title=The  Official Twitter of Mr. Peanut |url=https://twitter.com/MrPeanut/status/1082344496610922497 |website=Twitter.com |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n| image              =\n| caption            = Mr. Peanut at Times Square\n| first              = 1916\n| last               = \n| voice              = [[Robert Downey Jr.]] (2010\u20132013)<br>[[Bill Hader]] (2013\u2013present)\n| creator            = Antonio Gentile\n| lbl1               = Company\n| data1              = [[Kraft Heinz]]\n| species            = [[A. hypogaea]]\n| gender             = Male\n| occupation         = [[Mascot]], [[gentleman]], [[hero]]\n}}\n'''Lydell Chrono Jones''' is the advertising [[logo]] and [[mascot]] of [[Planters]], an American snack-food company and division of [[Kraft Heinz]] based in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. He is depicted as an [[anthropomorphic]] [[peanut]] in its shell dressed in the formal clothing of an old-fashioned [[gentleman]]: [[top hat]], [[monocle]], white gloves, [[Spat (footwear)|spats]], and a cane. He is reportedly of British heritage and has the proper name of Bartholomew Richard Fitzgerald-Smythe.<ref name=FullName/><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Chronicle of Hats in Enjoyable Quotes: History of Fashion Accessories Series|last=Tomshinsky|first=Ida|date=2013-05-20|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-4797-9909-1|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mr. Peanut balloon lands in children's park.jpg|thumb|A [[hot air balloon]] in the shape of Mr. Peanut]]\n[[File:Introducing Mr Peanut ad.png|thumb|left|Newspaper ad, introducing Mr. Peanut to the public, dated 1917.]]\nPlanters Peanut Company was founded in 1906, in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], by [[Amedeo Obici]] and was incorporated two years later as the Planters Nut and Chocolate Company. In 1916, a young schoolboy, Antonio Gentile, submitted drawings of an anthropomorphic peanut to a design contest. After Gentile's design was chosen, the commercial artist Andrew S. Wallach added the monocle, top hat, and cane to create the iconic image. While Gentile's family originally received five dollars for winning the contest, Obici befriended them and paid Antonio\u2019s, and four of his siblings', way through college. After Obici paid Antonio's way through medical school, he became a doctor in [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]], where he died of a heart attack in 1939.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolknewsherald.com/2013/10/18/the-father-of-mr-peanut/|title=The father of Mr. Peanut - The Suffolk News-Herald|work=suffolknewsherald.com}}</ref>\n\nThere is a disputed claim that Frank P. Krize Sr., a Wilkes-Barre artist and head of the Suffolk plant, made the additions of the monocle, top hat and cane. Andrew Wallach's daughter, Virginia, maintains that Krize joined the project after Mr. Peanut was created. Neither Planter's history nor other sources still in circulation positively identify the artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peanutpals.org/|title=Mr. Peanut Collectors Club|work=peanutpals.org}}</ref><ref name=\"planters_history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planters.com/history.aspx?section=timeline|title=Planters History of the Planter Nut: Timeline|accessdate=June 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy the mid-1930s, the raffish figure had come to symbolize the entire peanut industry. Mr. Peanut has appeared on almost every Planters package and advertisement. He is now one of the best-known [[logo|icons]] in advertising history.<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AoWlCmNDA3QC&pg=PT422&dq=planters+%22mr+peanut%22#v=onepage&q=planters%20%22mr%20peanut%22&f=false\n|title=The Oxford companion to American food and drink\n|last=Smith\n|first=Andrew F.\n|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]\n|pages=\n|year=2007\n|accessdate=December 6, 2010 |isbn= 978-0-19-530796-2 }}</ref>\n[[File:Mr. Peanut Goes to War.jpg|thumb|upright|Mr. Peanut goes to war poster by the [[United States Department of Agriculture]]|alt=]]\nMr. Peanut has appeared in many [[TV commercials]] as an [[animated cartoon]] character. More recent commercials have shown him stop motion animated in a real-world setting.\n\nIn 2006, Planters conducted an online contest to determine whether to add a [[bow tie]], [[cufflinks]], or a [[pocketwatch]] to Mr. Peanut. The public voted for no change. {{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nWhile the character's television commercials were often accompanied by an elegant accented narrator, Mr. Peanut never had dialogue. On November 8, 2010, Planters announced that actor [[Robert Downey Jr.]] would become Mr. Peanut's first-ever voice actor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/08/business/media/08adco.html|title=Mr. Peanut\u2019s New Look? Old School|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=November 7, 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 22, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Mr. Peanut's \"stunt double\" named Peanut Butter Doug was introduced to tie in with the Planter's Peanut Butter launch. The character is voiced by [[Kevin Dillon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gluttoner.com/mr-peanut-now-selling-planters-peanut-butter/|title=Mr. Peanut Now Selling Planters Peanut Butter|work=gluttoner.com}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2013, Planters cast comedian and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' alumnus [[Bill Hader]] as the voice for a campaign focusing on its Planters Nut-rition product line.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/01/business/media/look-whos-talking-for-mr-peanut-now.html|title=Look Who\u2019s Talking for Mr. Peanut Now|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=July 1, 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 22, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Virginia General Assembly]] passed a joint resolution commending Mr. Peanut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?171+sum+HJ796|title=HJ796 Commending Mr. Peanut|work=Virginia LIS}}</ref>\n\n=== Baby Nut ===\nOn January 22, 2020, Planters released a teaser for its [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[Super Bowl commercials|commercial]] featuring Mr. Peanut, [[Wesley Snipes]] and [[Matt Walsh (comedian)|Matt Walsh]]. The trio were shown hanging onto a branch after accidentally driving the [[Nutmobile]] off a cliff to avoid an [[armadillo]], with Mr. Peanut electing to let go and fall to his death onto the Nutmobile, which then explodes. The company's social media outlets stated that his funeral would be the subject of Planters' Super Bowl ad.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://adage.com/article/special-report-super-bowl/planters-really-has-killed-mr-peanut-funeral-planned-super-bowl/2229566|title=Planters really has killed off Mr. Peanut, with a funeral planned for the Super Bowl|date=January 22, 2020|website=adage.com|language=en|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/rest-in-peace-mr-peanut-planters-kills-off-iconic-mascot-in-the-lead-up-to-super-bowl/|title=Mr. Peanut Is Killed in Teaser for Planters Super Bowl Ad|work=Adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/super-bowl-commercials-2020-mr-peanut-dies-bill-nye-makes-a-green-plea/|title=Super Bowl commercials 2020: Mr. Peanut dies and Bill Nye makes a green plea|last=Cooper|first=Gael Fashingbauer|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nPlanters suspended the campaign shortly after the [[2020 Calabasas helicopter crash]] which resulted in the death of everyone on board the flight, including former [[NBA]] player [[Kobe Bryant]] on January 26. They eventually resumed the campaign with the Super Bowl commercial, which showed Snipes and Walsh presiding over the funeral of Mr. Peanut, also attended by fellow mascots [[Kool-Aid Man]] and [[Mr. Clean]]. However, Kool-Aid Man's tears combined with sunlight cause a new, younger incarnation of Mr. Peanut, dubbed \"Baby Nut\", to grow from the soil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/hes-alive-kool-aid-mans-tears-resurrect-mr-peanut-in-planters-super-bowl-spot/|title=Here's How Mr. Peanut Was Resurrected During the Super Bowl|website=Adweek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nSince the premiere of the commercial, the Planters [[Twitter]] account has been used to make posts in-character as Baby Nut. It also retweeted posts from several Baby Nut meme accounts created before the ad aired, prompting Twitter to suspend them under the presumption that they were created by the company's agency to manipulate the platform in violation of its terms of use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/3/21120615/twitter-planters-baby-nut-memes-account-suspension-rules-spam|title=Twitter boots Planters\u2019 Baby Nut meme accounts for violating its rules|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=2020-02-03|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> \n\nThe campaign faced a mixed reaction from viewers, while comparisons were drawn between the character and other juvenile incarnations of characters seen in media, such as \"[[The Child (Star Wars)|Baby Yoda]]\" of ''[[The Mandalorian]]'', and [[Groot]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6498543/baby-nut-yoda-super-bowl/|title=Baby Nut or Baby Yoda? Planters\u2019 Super Bowl commercial sparks debate|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/eat-baby-nut-planters-baby-yoda/|title=The internet wants to grind Baby Nut into peanut butter for Baby Yoda|last=Yeo|first=Amanda|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nExplaining the intent of the campaign, a spokesman for Planters's advertising agency cited the examples of superhero deaths in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] for how such a death could connect with viewers and potential customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/23/planters-ad-agency-vaynermedia-explains-why-they-killed-off-mr-peanut.html|title=Planters ad agency VaynerMedia explains why they killed off Mr. Peanut|date=January 23, 2020|work=[[CNBC]]|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> Prior to the Super Bowl ad's premiere, a company spokesperson told ''[[Ad Age]]'' that they had not ruled out the scenario being a [[comic book death]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==In literature==\n* In the 2010 novel ''Mr. Peanut'' by [[Adam Ross (author)|Adam Ross]], a man fantasizes about killing his [[peanut allergy|peanut-allergic]] wife by force-feeding her peanuts.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/27/books/review/Turow-t.html Sunday Book Review, \"Death Match\"], ''[[New York Times]]''</ref>  \"He poured out a handful and ate them and then wiped the salt from his empty hand on his pants.  He looked at the chipper Planters Peanuts man tipping his top hat hello and thought about how one bite could kill Alice dead.\"<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zm3ozVKJ8WYC&pg=PA285&dq=planters+peanuts+tipping+alice#v=onepage&q=tipping%20hat&f=false\n|title=Mr. Peanut\n|last=Ross\n|first=Adam\n|publisher=Borzoi Books\n|page=265\n|year=2010\n|accessdate=December 6, 2010 |isbn= 978-0-307-27070-2 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Mr Peanut Sculpture on Bench at Atlantic City 01.jpg|thumb|Sculpture of Mr. Peanut seated (left) on a bench in Atlantic City, NJ, August 2006. The sculpture was later removed.]]\n* The artist Vincent Trasov, dressed as Mr. Peanut, ran as a [[joke candidate]] in the 1974 [[Vancouver]], British Columbia civic elections.<ref>{{cite news|last=Milroy|first=Sarah|title=Mr. Peanut's lasting impact on Vancouver|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/mr-peanuts-lasting-impact-on-vancouver/article4574604/|accessdate=August 19, 2013|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=September 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.planters.com/mr-peanut Planters.com: History of the Planters Nut]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peanut}}\n[[Category:Food advertising characters|Peanut, Mister]]\n[[Category:Corporate mascots|Peanut, Mister]]\n[[Category:Fictional food characters]]\n[[Category:Fruit and vegetable characters|Peanut, Mister]]\n[[Category:Kraft Foods brands|Peanut, Mister]]\n[[Category:Mascots introduced in 1916]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mascot for Planters Peanuts}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mr. Peanut\n| full_name          = Bartholomew Richard Fitzgerald-Smythe<ref name=FullName>{{cite web |title=The  Official Twitter of Mr. Peanut |url=https://twitter.com/MrPeanut/status/1082344496610922497 |website=Twitter.com |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n| image              =\n| caption            = Mr. Peanut at Times Square\n| first              = 1916\n| last               = \n| voice              = [[Robert Downey Jr.]] (2010\u20132013)<br>[[Bill Hader]] (2013\u2013present)\n| creator            = Antonio Gentile\n| lbl1               = Company\n| data1              = [[Kraft Heinz]]\n| species            = [[A. hypogaea]]\n| gender             = Male\n| occupation         = [[Mascot]], [[gentleman]], [[hero]]\n}}\n'''Mr. Peanut''' is the advertising [[logo]] and [[mascot]] of [[Planters]], an American snack-food company and division of [[Kraft Heinz]] based in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. He is depicted as an [[anthropomorphic]] [[peanut]] in its shell dressed in the formal clothing of an old-fashioned [[gentleman]]: [[top hat]], [[monocle]], white gloves, [[Spat (footwear)|spats]], and a cane. He is reportedly of British heritage and has the proper name of Bartholomew Richard Fitzgerald-Smythe.<ref name=FullName/><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Chronicle of Hats in Enjoyable Quotes: History of Fashion Accessories Series|last=Tomshinsky|first=Ida|date=2013-05-20|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-4797-9909-1|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mr. Peanut balloon lands in children's park.jpg|thumb|A [[hot air balloon]] in the shape of Mr. Peanut]]\n[[File:Introducing Mr Peanut ad.png|thumb|left|Newspaper ad, introducing Mr. Peanut to the public, dated 1917.]]\nPlanters Peanut Company was founded in 1906, in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], by [[Amedeo Obici]] and was incorporated two years later as the Planters Nut and Chocolate Company. In 1916, a young schoolboy, Antonio Gentile, submitted drawings of an anthropomorphic peanut to a design contest. After Gentile's design was chosen, the commercial artist Andrew S. Wallach added the monocle, top hat, and cane to create the iconic image. While Gentile's family originally received five dollars for winning the contest, Obici befriended them and paid Antonio\u2019s, and four of his siblings', way through college. After Obici paid Antonio's way through medical school, he became a doctor in [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]], where he died of a heart attack in 1939.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolknewsherald.com/2013/10/18/the-father-of-mr-peanut/|title=The father of Mr. Peanut - The Suffolk News-Herald|work=suffolknewsherald.com}}</ref>\n\nThere is a disputed claim that Frank P. Krize Sr., a Wilkes-Barre artist and head of the Suffolk plant, made the additions of the monocle, top hat and cane. Andrew Wallach's daughter, Virginia, maintains that Krize joined the project after Mr. Peanut was created. Neither Planter's history nor other sources still in circulation positively identify the artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peanutpals.org/|title=Mr. Peanut Collectors Club|work=peanutpals.org}}</ref><ref name=\"planters_history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planters.com/history.aspx?section=timeline|title=Planters History of the Planter Nut: Timeline|accessdate=June 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy the mid-1930s, the raffish figure had come to symbolize the entire peanut industry. Mr. Peanut has appeared on almost every Planters package and advertisement. He is now one of the best-known [[logo|icons]] in advertising history.<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AoWlCmNDA3QC&pg=PT422&dq=planters+%22mr+peanut%22#v=onepage&q=planters%20%22mr%20peanut%22&f=false\n|title=The Oxford companion to American food and drink\n|last=Smith\n|first=Andrew F.\n|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]\n|pages=\n|year=2007\n|accessdate=December 6, 2010 |isbn= 978-0-19-530796-2 }}</ref>\n[[File:Mr. Peanut Goes to War.jpg|thumb|upright|Mr. Peanut goes to war poster by the [[United States Department of Agriculture]]|alt=]]\nMr. Peanut has appeared in many [[TV commercials]] as an [[animated cartoon]] character. More recent commercials have shown him stop motion animated in a real-world setting.\n\nIn 2006, Planters conducted an online contest to determine whether to add a [[bow tie]], [[cufflinks]], or a [[pocketwatch]] to Mr. Peanut. The public voted for no change. {{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nWhile the character's television commercials were often accompanied by an elegant accented narrator, Mr. Peanut never had dialogue. On November 8, 2010, Planters announced that actor [[Robert Downey Jr.]] would become Mr. Peanut's first-ever voice actor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/08/business/media/08adco.html|title=Mr. Peanut\u2019s New Look? Old School|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=November 7, 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 22, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Mr. Peanut's \"stunt double\" named Peanut Butter Doug was introduced to tie in with the Planter's Peanut Butter launch. The character is voiced by [[Kevin Dillon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gluttoner.com/mr-peanut-now-selling-planters-peanut-butter/|title=Mr. Peanut Now Selling Planters Peanut Butter|work=gluttoner.com}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2013, Planters cast comedian and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' alumnus [[Bill Hader]] as the voice for a campaign focusing on its Planters Nut-rition product line.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/01/business/media/look-whos-talking-for-mr-peanut-now.html|title=Look Who\u2019s Talking for Mr. Peanut Now|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=July 1, 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 22, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Virginia General Assembly]] passed a joint resolution commending Mr. Peanut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?171+sum+HJ796|title=HJ796 Commending Mr. Peanut|work=Virginia LIS}}</ref>\n\n=== Baby Nut ===\nOn January 22, 2020, Planters released a teaser for its [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[Super Bowl commercials|commercial]] featuring Mr. Peanut, [[Wesley Snipes]] and [[Matt Walsh (comedian)|Matt Walsh]]. The trio were shown hanging onto a branch after accidentally driving the [[Nutmobile]] off a cliff to avoid an [[armadillo]], with Mr. Peanut electing to let go and fall to his death onto the Nutmobile, which then explodes. The company's social media outlets stated that his funeral would be the subject of Planters' Super Bowl ad.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://adage.com/article/special-report-super-bowl/planters-really-has-killed-mr-peanut-funeral-planned-super-bowl/2229566|title=Planters really has killed off Mr. Peanut, with a funeral planned for the Super Bowl|date=January 22, 2020|website=adage.com|language=en|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/rest-in-peace-mr-peanut-planters-kills-off-iconic-mascot-in-the-lead-up-to-super-bowl/|title=Mr. Peanut Is Killed in Teaser for Planters Super Bowl Ad|work=Adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/super-bowl-commercials-2020-mr-peanut-dies-bill-nye-makes-a-green-plea/|title=Super Bowl commercials 2020: Mr. Peanut dies and Bill Nye makes a green plea|last=Cooper|first=Gael Fashingbauer|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nPlanters suspended the campaign shortly after the [[2020 Calabasas helicopter crash]] which resulted in the death of everyone on board the flight, including former [[NBA]] player [[Kobe Bryant]] on January 26. They eventually resumed the campaign with the Super Bowl commercial, which showed Snipes and Walsh presiding over the funeral of Mr. Peanut, also attended by fellow mascots [[Kool-Aid Man]] and [[Mr. Clean]]. However, Kool-Aid Man's tears combined with sunlight cause a new, younger incarnation of Mr. Peanut, dubbed \"Baby Nut\", to grow from the soil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/hes-alive-kool-aid-mans-tears-resurrect-mr-peanut-in-planters-super-bowl-spot/|title=Here's How Mr. Peanut Was Resurrected During the Super Bowl|website=Adweek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nSince the premiere of the commercial, the Planters [[Twitter]] account has been used to make posts in-character as Baby Nut. It also retweeted posts from several Baby Nut meme accounts created before the ad aired, prompting Twitter to suspend them under the presumption that they were created by the company's agency to manipulate the platform in violation of its terms of use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/3/21120615/twitter-planters-baby-nut-memes-account-suspension-rules-spam|title=Twitter boots Planters\u2019 Baby Nut meme accounts for violating its rules|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=2020-02-03|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> \n\nThe campaign faced a mixed reaction from viewers, while comparisons were drawn between the character and other juvenile incarnations of characters seen in media, such as \"[[The Child (Star Wars)|Baby Yoda]]\" of ''[[The Mandalorian]]'', and [[Groot]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.c